        "trailText":"<p><strong>Laura Bates:</strong> Ada Lovelace Day has put the focus on women in science. The Everyday Sexism Project invited scientists and engineers to tweet about their experiences</p>",
        "headline":"Women in science: 'Whoa, what are you doing here?'",
        "body":"<p>This week saw a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/oct/15/nerd-cabaret-wikipedia-ada-lovelace-day-2013\" title=\"\">day of celebration for Ada Lovelace</a>, a brilliant mathematician who wrote the world's first computer program before computers were even invented. Lovelace grew up in a world of enormous gender inequality, and her first experience of it came moments after birth with her father's reported disappointment that she was not \"the glorious boy\" he had hoped for. But even now, nearly 200 years later, women in science, technology, engineering and mathematics (Stem) are still fighting an uphill battle against professional gender imbalance.</p><p>According to <a href=\"http://www.e-skills.com/research/research-publications/women-in-it/\" title=\"\">e-skills UK</a>, women make up just 17% of the UK IT and telecoms workforce. And the number of women in the most senior research positions in Stem in the UK also stands at the paltry figure of 17%, according to a <a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/science-and-technology-committee/inquiries/parliament-2010/women-in-stem-careers/\" title=\"\">2012 European Commission study</a>. Even worse, according to a <a href=\"http://www.wisecampaign.org.uk/files/useruploads/files/wise_stats_document_final.pdf\" title=\"\">2012 Wise campaign report (pdf)</a> only 13% of Stem jobs in the UK are occupied by women.</p><p>So why has progress been so slow since Lovelace blazed her trail some two centuries ago? Partly because women in Stem are still battling attitudes towards women that belong in the 19th century. To celebrate Ada Lovelace day, the <a href=\"http://www.everydaysexism.com\" title=\"\">Everyday Sexism Project</a> invited women on Twitter to share their experiences in Stem careers, good or bad. Many positive stories were shared, with one woman saying she was \"so proud of my electrical engineer mother who's been head of her department for 20+ years\" and others reporting positive moves in the right direction …</p><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a> My fantastic male science teacher encouraged me into science BECAUSE I'm a woman, not in spite of. Final year neurosci now!</p><p>&mdash; Katie Clements (@katie_elvira) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/katie_elvira/statuses/390098784975208449\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a> I'm a female PhD on a course directed by a woman. Primary supervisor is female as are many of the Dept's best researchers :)</p><p>&mdash; Alice-Emma-Louise (@AliceEmmaLouise) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/AliceEmmaLouise/statuses/390074047301955584\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a> Part of mostly female research group working in coding/physics/fieldwork heavy area. Love it.</p><p>&mdash; Hayley Evers-King (@HayleyEversKing) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/HayleyEversKing/statuses/390063639002370048\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><p>But these stories were far outweighed by the tales that flooded in from women in Stem careers facing sheer archaic sexism at every turn. From the decision to go into the field in the first place …</p><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>.<a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a> I was warned off software dev by female HR person who told me it was all men and v hard for women - told her I didn't care.</p><p>&mdash; Rosey Tyler (@RoseyTyler) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/RoseyTyler/statuses/390060258422710272\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/Eilidhcraig\">@Eilidhcraig</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a> I got the variant of that \" you are too pretty to do science.\"</p><p>&mdash; Eims (@bugamonster) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/bugamonster/statuses/390080895463735296\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><p>… to studying Stem …</p><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a> - studying engineering, maths lecture described a graph and why all the women would recognise it as shaped like washing line</p><p>&mdash; Ethel Fletcher (@EthelFletcher) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EthelFletcher/statuses/390095872790634496\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>My CompSci Mstrs orientation:&#10;Lecturer: Why are there so few women in CS?&#10;Male student: Because men are better programmers. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a></p><p>&mdash; Sofie Bird (@sofie_bird) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/sofie_bird/statuses/390054645759893504\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><p>… to challenges when trying to advance in their careers …</p><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>as lab tech saving money for grad school, i was told that, if i wanted letter of rec, i had to \"sleep with\" my boss <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@everydaysexism</a></p><p>&mdash; GrrlScientist (@GrrlScientist) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/GrrlScientist/statuses/390057263114641408\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/huhsmile\">@huhsmile</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a> this also happened when i was a postdoc looking for a job in science. i refused. ended up chronically unemployed.</p><p>&mdash; GrrlScientist (@GrrlScientist) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/GrrlScientist/statuses/390060105946771456\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><p>… to facing sexism on the job itself …</p><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>.<a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23ALD13&amp;src=hash\">#ALD13</a> I work in biology lab, repeatedly called \"wifey\" by a male academic and leered at, lude remarks made. Charming</p><p>&mdash; Dr Rachael Dunlop (@DrRachie) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/DrRachie/statuses/390058802776535040\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a> I stopped working in the IT-Sector as I never have been taken serious. Good enough to make coffee though &amp; to get sent porn.</p><p>&mdash; Canan (@_Canan__) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/_Canan__/statuses/390055421811384320\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a> one of few women at IT conference when doing my Masters. Man turned round, saw me &amp; said \"Whoa, what are you doing here?\"</p><p>&mdash; Jane (@ephemera_jane) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/ephemera_jane/statuses/390100203006480384\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a> I'm a mech engineer, got told at an industry function \"you don't look like an engineer\".  I asked him if it was the breasts.</p><p>&mdash; Karen Hovenga (@khovenga) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/khovenga/statuses/390095358363070464\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><p>Some people complained that by sharing these stories we would put even more girls off going into Stem. But they are stories that need to be heard. What message does it send to the scores of women facing this outdated, unacceptable discrimination, if they are told to put up and shut up to avoid putting off more women unwittingly signing up to face the same treatment? Burying our heads in the sand won't solve the problem, it'll just make it even more invisible and normalised.</p><p>Far better to get these stories out in the open; to scream and shout about them until something is done. And something does need to be done, because these are just a tiny number of the hundreds of examples we have collected. But the good news is that women aren't taking it lying down. Tomorrow's budding female scientists can take joyful motivation from these strong, inspirational women …</p><blockquote><p>\"I used to purposefully jam the copier so people would stop asking me to make photocopies for their meetings. I'm an engineer.\" Everyday Sexism Project entry</p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a> Aged 10: mocked mercilessly at school cos I said I was going to be a scientist with a lab with loads of cool stuff in it...</p><p>&mdash; Cath Aubergine (@CathAubergine) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/CathAubergine/statuses/390094310462332929\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a> ...Aged 41: I'm actually an engineer (semiconductor failure analysis), and I DO have a lab with loads of cool stuff in it :)</p><p>&mdash; Cath Aubergine (@CathAubergine) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/CathAubergine/statuses/390094389076193280\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>TV eng: TV needs a new tube love, pricey&#10;Me: That's a split capacitor fix it for free or I report you <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a></p><p>&mdash; Lovelyjane (@reallovelyjane) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/reallovelyjane/statuses/390077107474530304\">October 15, 2013</a></p><p><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"></p><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/TonyTimes2\">@TonyTimes2</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a> Free repair, and an apology.</p><p>&mdash; Lovelyjane (@reallovelyjane) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/reallovelyjane/statuses/390082386366840832\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><p></blockquote></p><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Careers teacher said he'd eat my indentures if I became engineer. Took them &amp; salt to school 5 years later. Got banned <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EverydaySexism\">@EverydaySexism</a></p><p>&mdash; Lovelyjane (@reallovelyjane) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/reallovelyjane/statuses/390066866066300928\">October 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420245157|2013-10-17T12:53:06Z|3a2edc26a3b33edcede957bdc6f5635993112335 -->",
