      "id":"lifeandstyle/2013/oct/17/top-five-chocolate-wine-coffee-pairings",
      "sectionId":"lifeandstyle",
      "sectionName":"Life and style",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T12:03:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Top five: chocolate pairings",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2013/oct/17/top-five-chocolate-wine-coffee-pairings",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/lifeandstyle/2013/oct/17/top-five-chocolate-wine-coffee-pairings",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p>It's National Chocolate week - and if you are in need of inspiration to indulge, why not try matching your chocolate with your drink?</p>",
        "headline":"Top five: chocolate pairings",
        "body":"<figure data-media-id='gu-image-420252791'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Lifeandhealth/Pix/pictures/2013/10/16/1381919237102/Lindt-excellence-bars-008.jpg' alt='Lindt excellence bars' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><h2><a href=\"http://www.lindt-shop.co.uk/chocolate-bars/excellence.html\">Lindt Excellence bars from £1.83</a><br /></h2><p>If there is a moment or a menu with which it is not appropriate to scoff a bar of Lindt Excellence Extra Creamy chocolate, I have yet to discover it. Possibly in the shower, though I'd give it my best shot. However, if you are a tad more discerning, then head to the <a href=\"http://www.lindt-excellence.co.uk\">Lindt website,</a> which has the best ways to mix/match your chocolates with coffee and alcohol. Not simultaneously, though then again, why not? Suggested pairings include the dark caramel with a touch of sea salt bar and prosecco, and the high-cocoa 90% bar with a milky latte. Sounds like excellent advice to me (sorry). </p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-420252792'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Lifeandhealth/Pix/pictures/2013/10/16/1381919280239/Hotel-Chocolat-gin-and-pr-008.jpg' alt='Hotel Chocolat gin and prosecco' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><h2><a href=\"http://www.hotelchocolat.com/uk/shop/collections/products/cooking-chocolate/dry-gin\">Hotel Chocolat cocoa gin, £15, </a><a href=\"http://www.hotelchocolat.com/uk/shop/collections/products/wine-chocolate/classic-prosecco\">and prosecco, £18</a></h2><p>Prosecco seems to be the alcoholic beverage of choice when it comes to scoffing and boozing. Hotel Chocolat has branched out into its own food and wine/spirits range, including this excellent fizz from Valdobbiadene, near Venice. The gin is a very tasty new addition, made in England but using the spices and flavours from the company's estate in Saint Lucia. As it's made using cocoa shells, it's a booze-and-chocolate-pairing of sorts in one bottle. Alternatively, you can peruse the wine list from the restaurant on that Saint Lucia estate and daydream of a trip there. Take me with you.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-420252790'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Lifeandhealth/Pix/pictures/2013/10/17/1382008138311/Amelia-Rope-chocolate--008.jpg' alt='Amelia Rope chocolate\n' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><h2><a href=\"http://www.ameliarope.com/chocolate-bars/flavoured-chocolate-bars/\">Amelia Rope chocolate, from £5.60</a></h2><p>True chocolate connoisseurs may already be familiar with <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2013/jun/22/meet-the-producer-chocolatier-amelia-rope\">Amelia Rope's prize-winning bars. </a>  She has suggested some pairings for her own creations:<br /><strong>White chocolate with sea salt</strong><br /><a href=\"http://groceries.asda.com/asda-webstore/landing/home.shtml#!product/910000852724\">Asda's Extra Special Moscatel NV £4.50</a> is great with this and a bargain too. It is ripe and full with an orange zest aroma.<br /><strong>Pale lemon and sea salt</strong><br />Fabulous with a young Madeira such as a five-year-old. You get a lovely match between the citrus acidity of the Madeira and the rich acidity of the pale lemon – also rather good with the pale lime bar. Another good choice would be a light Prosecco.<br /><strong>Dark Ginger</strong><br />Pair with a sweet <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juran%C3%A7on_AOC\">Jurancon</a>, such as <a href=\"http://www.ocado.com/webshop/product/Chateau-Jolys-Cuvee-Jean-Jurancon-Sweet-Wine/36012011\">Chateau Jolys Cuvee Jean</a>. Or the lovely <a href=\"http://thekingsginger.com/\">King's Ginger Liqueur</a> or be bold with <a href=\"http://www.crabbiesgingerbeer.co.uk/\">Crabbie's Original Alcoholic Ginger Beer</a>.<br /><strong>Pale Rose</strong><br />Match with a <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kriek_lambic\">Belgian Kriek beer</a> (brewed with cherries) such as <a href=\"http://www.liefmans.be/en\">Liefmann's</a>: two lovely aromas to match.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-420252793'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Lifeandhealth/Pix/pictures/2013/10/16/1381934039066/Valrhona-Jivara-chocolate-008.jpg' alt='Valrhona Jivara chocolate' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><h2><a href=\"http://www.chocolatetradingco.com/chocolates/brand/valrhona\">Valhrona chocolate, from £2.95</a></h2><p>If beer floats your boat more than the produce of the vineyard, then check out <a href=\"http://www.valrhona-chocolate.com/beerpairings\">Valhrona's website for a long list of possible matches</a> made in brewery heaven. Beers, ales, stouts and bitters are all matched with the appropriate level of cocoa content. Examples include their 64% dark chocolate with a cherry wheat beer, or the 85% with an Imperial or a traditional British milk stout. The site does also have a <a href=\"https://valrhona-chocolate.3dcartstores.com/winepairings\">good wine-matching section</a> to browse.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-420252794'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Lifeandhealth/Pix/pictures/2013/10/16/1381934556973/Green-and-Blacks-collecti-016.jpg' alt='Green and Blacks collection' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><h2><a href=\"http://www.greenandblacksdirect.com/p/237/green-blacks-connoisseur-collection\">Green &amp; Blacks connoisseur collection, £17.99<br /></a></h2><p>This box set, an edited selection of the many tasty bars in the Green &amp; Blacks range, comes with a rather pretty wheel on the inside lid of the box, showing which products go best with which wines – but also with which foods. For instance, chocolate with … oh hell, just everything, OK?</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420118843|2013-10-17T12:53:06Z|8cc2f72925332068ab28cfa2cafbad2e7