      "id":"lifeandstyle/2013/oct/16/waitrose-to-sell-beef-bone-marrow",
      "sectionId":"lifeandstyle",
      "sectionName":"Life and style",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-16T17:16:50Z",
      "webTitle":"Waitrose to sell beef bone marrow",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2013/oct/16/waitrose-to-sell-beef-bone-marrow",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/lifeandstyle/2013/oct/16/waitrose-to-sell-beef-bone-marrow",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"14",
        "trailText":"Supermarket adds delicacy popularised by restaurants such as St John to its range of 'forgotten' cuts of meat",
        "headline":"Waitrose to sell beef bone marrow",
        "body":"<p>It was cheap wartime food and became an unlikely, niche delicacy on the menus at some of London's top restaurants. Now bone marrow is making its way back on to the supermarket shelves.</p><p>Waitrose, which is also trying to revive other traditional and cheap cuts of meat such as kidney, belly pork, lamb's liver and oxtail, will start selling beef bone marrow this week in all its UK stores as part of its Forgotten Cuts range.</p><p>Waitrose's meat buyer Rob Hues said: \"Our customers have embraced the Forgotten Cuts we've introduced over the last five years – they understand that by adopting slow-cooking methods they will be able to create great value meals that pack in masses of flavour.\"</p><p>The chef Fergus Henderson, founder of the cult restaurant St John near London's Smithfield meat market, has made roast veal bone marrow – served with toast and a lemon-dressed parsley salad – his signature dish, always on the menu.</p><p>Bones bought from butchers were traditionally roasted upright and the marrow – a paste-like substance inside – extracted to be spread on toast or with salad or used as a base to enrich stock, soups, gravies and sauces. The marrow melts, then caramelises and can be subsequently re-constituted with liquid and aromatics. High in fat but also highly nutritious (rich in protein and fat-soluble vitamins A and D), it was popular in wartime to add much-needed flavour to soups, stews and other dishes.</p><p>Hues went on: \"Bone marrow has been a key ingredient in some of London's top meat restaurants such as Hawksmoor and St John's where they both promote the nose-to-tail dining experience. Those in the know understand that by adding bone marrow you can intensify meaty flavours.\"</p><p>The supermarket will enlist the help of its food ambassador Heston Blumenthal to put bone marrow top of Britons' shopping lists with a recipe for traditional minced beef and dumplings. It will be unveiled in a TV and print advertising campaign and supported in store with a recipe card and an introductory offer of one third off the price of a pack of diced beef shin with bone marrow.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420177128|2013-10-17T12:53:06Z|ee3d58609f2aac59dad11a72f46e189567f97d36 -->",
